98, and an analysis of the role of cavalry "coureurs" in late-medieval France. But regions further to the south and east are by no means neglected, with a dissection of the military rhetoric of Pere III of Aragon and his queen, Elionor of Sicily, and a discussion of the earliest European gunpowder recipes, from Friuli (1336) and Augsburg (1338- c. 1350). The volume also offers studies of the campaigns culminating in the battles of Firad in 634 and Qinnasr?n in 1134.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, MedievalvPeriodicals. 0aMilitary art and sciencevPeriodicalsxHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aMilitary history, MedievalvPeriodicals. 0aPolitics and warvPeriodicalsxHistoryyTo 1500zEurope. 0aWar and societyvPeriodicalsxHistoryyTo 1500zEurope. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aTechnology.  abattle tactics.  asoldiers.  awarfare.  awords.1 aAnsani, Fabrizio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlundell, Michael C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlundell, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeVries, Kelly, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrance, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGurinov, Evgeniy A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGurinov, Evgeniy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbinson, Michael J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarbinson, Michael John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKagay, Donald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPilling, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/